doc.after: Lock Haven is at 561 feet (171Â m) above sea level near the confluence of Bald Eagle Creek and the West Branch Susquehanna River in north-central Pennsylvania.[2][37] The city is about 200 miles (320Â km) by highway northwest of Philadelphia and 175 miles (280Â km) northeast of Pittsburgh.[38] U.S. Route 220, a major transportation corridor, skirts the city on its south edge, intersecting with Pennsylvania Route 120, which passes through the city and connects it with Renovo in northern Clinton County. Other highways entering Lock Haven include Pennsylvania Route 664 and Pennsylvania Route 150, which connects to Avis.[37]
